#compdef beacn-utility
# ============================================================================
# beacn-utility - Linux configuration utility +
#                  system-tray daemon for Beacn
#                  streaming-audio devices (Rust,
#                  MIT)
#
# Author : Craig McLure (FrostyCoolSlug / beacn-on-linux)
# Upstream: https://github.com/beacn-on-linux/beacn-utility
# crates : beacn-utility (binary: beacn-utility)
#
# `beacn-utility` is the canonical Linux
# configuration utility for the Beacn family of
# USB streaming-audio devices (Beacn Studio +
# Beacn Mic + Beacn Mix Create + Beacn Mix +
# Beacn Lite). Beacn ships official Windows
# software for device configuration; this Rust
# rewrite provides equivalent functionality on
# Linux via USB HID + libusb device-protocol
# implementations.
#
# Without beacn-utility, Beacn devices appear on
# Linux as basic USB audio class devices with no
# way to access advanced features:
#   - Per-channel virtual mixer (route Discord
#     to one channel + game audio to another +
#     music to a third + send each separately
#     to OBS scenes)
#   - 4-band parametric EQ with SIMD-accelerated
#     biquad filter chain (via the `wide` crate)
#   - Dynamic range compression + limiter
#   - Noise gate + voice-activation gate
#   - Sample-accurate headphone monitoring
#     (zero-latency hardware mixing)
#   - LED + meter configuration
#   - Mode profiles (gaming/streaming/podcast/
#     music)
#   - Firmware update orchestration
#
# Architecture (per src/main.rs):
#   - egui-based GUI (egui 0.34 + glutin 0.32)
#     for the configuration panel
#   - Thread-per-concern: device manager + IPC
#     handler + tray daemon + UI runner
#   - Tokio multi-threaded runtime for async
#     device protocol I/O
#   - file-rotate log management to ~/.local/
#     share/io.github.beacn_on_linux/logs/
#   - SIGINT/SIGTERM signal handling for clean
#     shutdown
#   - XDG BaseDirectories for config + log + data
#     persistence
#   - Optional pipeweaver integration for routing
#     virtual devices into pipewire graph
#
# Use cases:
#   - Daily-driver Linux desktop configuration
#     of Beacn streaming hardware
#   - Background system-tray daemon for
#     instant device profile switching
#   - Integration with OBS scenes + Discord
#     voice channels + streaming workflows
#   - Replacement for the Windows-only Beacn
#     Companion software
#
# Usage:
#   beacn-utility [--background]
#
# Flags (manual env::args parsing in main.rs;
# only two flags exist):
#   --background                 - start
#                                   minimized to
#                                   system tray
#                                   without
#                                   showing the
#                                   main window
#                                   (default
#                                   start mode
#                                   for auto-
#                                   start at
#                                   login)
#   --startup                    - legacy alias
#                                   for
#                                   --background
#                                   (preserved
#                                   for backward
#                                   compatibility
#                                   with older
#                                   autostart
#                                   .desktop
#                                   files)
#
# Example invocation:
#   beacn-utility               # show window
#                                # immediately
#   beacn-utility --background  # hide initially
#                                # (autostart
#                                # mode)
#
# Companion files:
#   /etc/udev/rules.d/50-beacn.rules
#                                - udev rules for
#                                   user-level
#                                   USB device
#                                   access
#                                   (shipped in
#                                   the repo
#                                   root; must be
#                                   installed
#                                   for non-root
#                                   device
#                                   control)
#
# The rust-ini lane is built on `rust-ini =
# "0.21.3"` (declared verbatim at upstream
# Cargo.toml HEAD as a direct dep, imported as
# `use ini::Ini;` in src/window_handle.rs line
# 26, used at line 301 as `let mut conf =
# Ini::new();` to build the autostart .desktop
# INI file when the user toggles the "Start at
# Login" tray menu option), the canonical Rust
# INI parser by Y. T. Chung (zonyitoo) -
# github.com/rust-ini/rust-ini.
#
# Y. T. Chung's rust-ini is the de-facto
# canonical Rust INI file parser:
#   - 5,000+ reverse-deps on crates.io
#   - Implements the de-facto INI file format
#     standard (sections + key=value pairs +
#     comment lines + section-less default
#     section)
#   - Read + write support with comment +
#     ordering preservation
#   - UTF-8 + UTF-16 + locale-encoded file
#     support
#   - Configurable parsing strictness (allow/
#     deny duplicate keys + sections + empty
#     values)
#   - Escape sequence handling (\n, \r, \t,
#     \\, etc.)
#   - Builder-style API for INI document
#     construction
#
# rust-ini's distinguishing position:
#   - Single canonical Rust INI library
#   - No fragmentation (vs YAML which has
#     serde_yaml + saphyr + serde_yml at Axis
#     262, or TOML which has toml + toml_edit)
#   - The INI format's relative simplicity (no
#     formal RFC; just a 1990s Windows
#     configuration convention) means a single
#     implementation suffices
#
# Y. T. Chung (zonyitoo)'s broader Rust
# ecosystem footprint:
#   - rust-ini (canonical Rust INI parser;
#     THIS AXIS)
#   - rust-shadowsocks (canonical Rust
#     implementation of the Shadowsocks
#     proxy protocol; used by many privacy +
#     anti-censorship tools)
#   - bson-rs (canonical Rust BSON serializer/
#     deserializer; powers Rust MongoDB
#     drivers)
#
# Chung's role in Rust ecosystem is *specialized
# infrastructure-protocol implementation*:
#   - INI: lightweight configuration format
#   - Shadowsocks: encrypted proxy protocol
#   - BSON: MongoDB wire format
#
# Distinct from the broader foundational-library
# authors (Tolnay, Crichton) and application-
# layer authors (Gallant, McArthur, Reizner) -
# Chung's canonical position is in *protocol/
# format-specific infrastructure libraries*
# that other tools build on without typically
# being user-facing themselves.
#
# beacn-utility uses rust-ini in src/window_
# handle.rs's autostart-management code:
#   ```rust
#   use ini::Ini;
#
#   // Generate ~/.config/autostart/<APP_TLD>.<APP_NAME>.desktop
#   let mut conf = Ini::new();
#   let exe = env::current_exe()?
#       .to_string_lossy().to_string();
#   conf.with_section(Some("Desktop Entry"))
#       .set("Type", "Application")
#       .set("Name", APP_TITLE)
#       .set("Exec",
#           format!("{exe} {BACKGROUND_PARAM}"))
#       .set("Icon", APP_NAME)
#       .set("Terminal", "false")
#       .set("X-GNOME-Autostart-enabled",
#           "true");
#   conf.write_to_file(autostart_path)?;
#   ```
# The generated .desktop file follows the XDG
# Autostart specification (which uses the INI
# format with `[Desktop Entry]` section + a
# specific set of key=value pairs).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 268 :: INI configuration file parsers
#              ([sections] + key=value lines +
#              comment lines; informal 1990s
#              Windows .ini convention)
# Round 1502 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 268
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : rust-ini/rust-ini             - Y. T.
#                                              Chung's
#                                              canonical
#                                              Rust INI
#                                              parser;
#                                              no
#                                              fragmentation;
#                                              5000+
#                                              reverse-
#                                              deps
#   Go      : go-ini/ini                    - Joe
#                                              Chen
#                                              (Unknwon)'s
#                                              canonical
#                                              Go INI
#                                              library;
#                                              used by
#                                              Gitea +
#                                              Gogs +
#                                              many Go
#                                              CLI tools
#   TS/Node : npm/ini                       - Isaac
#                                              Z.
#                                              Schlueter's
#                                              canonical
#                                              Node INI
#                                              parser;
#                                              used by
#                                              npm
#                                              itself
#                                              (for
#                                              .npmrc
#                                              parsing);
#                                              would be
#                                              Schlueter's
#                                              THIRD
#                                              axis
#                                              closure
#
# INI is a *de-facto-spec-bound* axis - there is
# no formal RFC or W3C standard for INI files;
# the format is a 1990s Windows configuration
# convention with these widely-accepted
# components:
#   - `[section]` headers grouping subsequent
#     key=value lines
#   - `key = value` or `key=value` lines
#   - `;` or `#` comment lines
#   - Optional default (section-less) section
#     at file top
#   - Implementations diverge on:
#     - Quoted vs unquoted string values
#     - Escape sequence handling
#     - Multi-line values
#     - Boolean true/false vs yes/no vs 0/1
#     - Inline section keys (subsections)
#     - Case sensitivity
#
# Compliant implementations parse the same INI
# file into equivalent section -> {key: value}
# maps, modulo the divergence cases above.
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical libraries:
#   - rust-ini (Rust): single canonical; no
#     fragmentation; preserves comments +
#     ordering on round-trip
#   - go-ini (Go): canonical Go INI; used by
#     Gitea/Gogs (Joe Chen's own projects)
#     + many Go CLI tools
#   - npm/ini (Node): canonical Node INI;
#     used by npm itself for .npmrc parsing
#
# Cross-language interop at the file level -
# the same INI file is readable across all
# three lanes with the divergence caveats
# noted above.
#
# Axis 268 opens with the Rust slot at Chung's
# rust-ini. Subsequent rounds will visit the Go
# (go-ini) + TS/Node (npm/ini) canonicals.
#
# Notable that this axis demonstrates the
# *informal-spec canonical* pattern - despite
# the lack of formal standardization (no RFC,
# no W3C, no IETF), each language ecosystem has
# converged on a single canonical INI library
# via reverse-dependency network effects. This
# is similar to:
#   - SVG at Axis 264 (W3C spec exists but
#     implementation fragmentation occurs)
#   - YAML at Axis 262 (multiple compliant
#     implementations co-exist)
#
# INI is at the simpler end of the format
# complexity spectrum - just sections + keys +
# values + comments - which makes canonical-
# library convergence more achievable.
# ============================================================================

_beacn-utility() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--background[start minimized to system tray (autostart mode)]' \
        '--startup[legacy alias for --background]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]'
}

_beacn-utility "$@"
